Integrating oncogeriatric tools into the management of chronic lymphocytic 
leukemia: current state of the art and challenges for the future.

Merli F(1), Mammi C, Ilariucci F.

Author information:
(1)Hematology, Arcispedale S. Maria Nuova-IRCCS, Viale Risorgimento 80, 42123, 
Reggio Emilia, Italy, merli.francesco@asmn.re.it.

Although the achievement of deep and long lasting remissions is a realistic goal 
of therapy in the fit patient with chronic lymphocytic leukemia (CLL), this 
disease typically affects elderly patients who also show one or more concomitant 
pathological conditions or functional limitations that have an additive effects 
on the reduction of patient's life expectancy and represent major limitations in 
the adoption of standard therapies. In these unfit but typical patients with 
CLL, the goals of treatment may vary from achieving good remissions without 
severe toxicity to simple palliation. Differently from the past when the 
definition of patient medical status was mainly based on age and was left to the 
subjective assessment of the physician, today there are several tools to define 
in a standardized, reproducible, and multidimensional way the initial patient 
assessment and to plan treatment goals in an objective way. In this review, an 
overview of the current approaches to the definition of the medical fitness of 
the patient is provided along with some practical suggestions to integrate these 
tools in the clinical approach to elderly patients with CLL.

